        "title": "Priority ranking",
        "content": "1. **store.py** — the dedup/diff logic is the correctness backbone of the whole tool; a bug here means silent duplicate notifications or lost jobs. Zero coverage today.\n2. **fetchers.py `_request` + `parse_*`** — pure, fast, highest bug-surface (20 bespoke ATS integrations, each brittle to upstream HTML/JSON drift per your memory notes on Meta/Microsoft/ByteDance).\n3. **filters.py / models.py** — small and pure, cheap to fully cover, and `parse_posted_at`'s date-format handling silently drops jobs when wrong.\n4. **notify.py** — env-gating logic is easy to get backwards (e.g. accidentally SMS-blasting on partial config); worth locking in.\n5. **agent.py `cmd_db_new` group-truncation/watermark logic** — subtle boundary conditions that, if wrong, either skip jobs or repeat them in the LLM-facing scan digest.\n6. **pipeline.py / cli.py** — thin glue, low complexity, but a quick integration smoke test (`run()` end-to-end with mocked `fetch_all`) is cheap insurance.\n\nWant me to actually scaffold `tests/` and write out the full parser/fetcher test suite (all ~20 ATS parsers, not just the representative ones above), or would you rather I start with just store.py + models.py + filters.py since those are the highest-value/lowest-effort wins?",
        "level": 2
      }
    ],
    "codeBlocks": [
      {
        "language": "text",
        "code": "# requirements-dev.txt (new)\npytest>=8.0\npytest-asyncio>=0.24"
      },
      {
        "language": "python",
        "code": "# tests/conftest.py\nimport pytest, httpx\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef store(tmp_path):\n    from store import Store\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"test.db\") as s:\n        yield s\n\ndef mock_client(handler):\n    return httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler))"
      },
